'''Eustathios Argyros''' ({{lang-el|Εὐστάθιος Ἀργυρός}}; died ca. 910) was a [[Byzantine]] aristocrat and one of the most prominent generals under Emperor [[Leo VI the Wise]] (r. 886–912). The first member of the [[Argyros (Byzantine family)|Argyros family]] to rise to high posts, he fought with distinction against the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Arabs]] in the east, before being disgraced ca. 907, possibly in connection with the flight of [[Andronikos Doukas (general under Leo VI)|Andronikos Doukas]] to the Arabs. Rehabilitated soon after, he was appointed as ''[[strategos]]'' of [[Charsianon]], from which post he oversaw the settlement of [[Armenians|Armenian]] lords as march-wardens along the Empire's eastern frontier. Promoted to commander of the [[Vigla (tagma)|imperial bodyguard]] in late 908, he again fell into disgrace shortly after and died of poison (apparently a suicide) on his way to his estates.

== Life ==
Eustathios Argyros was the son of the ''[[tourmarches]]'' [[Leo Argyros (9th century)|Leo Argyros]], the founder of the noble [[Argyros (Byzantine family)|Argyros family]].{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|pp=58, 59}}{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}

Nothing is known of his life or prior to the turn of the 10th century, although he may have been in imperial service as early as 866, when a man of the same name is recorded as ''[[protostrator]]'' of the ''[[Caesar (title)|Caesar]]'' [[Bardas]] in connection with the latter's murder on 21 April.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=210}} The Byzantine historians praise Eustathios Argyros as an intelligent, valiant, prudent and just man, and account him, along with [[Andronikos Doukas (general under Leo VI)|Andronikos Doukas]], as the best of Leo VI's generals.{{sfn|Guilland|1967|pp=570–571}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|pp=207–208}} The historians Jean-Claude Cheynet and Jean-François Vannier, experts on Byzantine prosopography, consider him "the true founder of the family's glory".{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}

[[File:Arab-Byzantine frontier zone.svg|thumb|250px|Map of the Arab–Byzantine frontier zone]]
Although he is sometimes identified with an admiral active in ca. 902–904 (see [[#Identity|below]]), his life is only securely attested after 904.{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=210}} At this time, evidently after a succession of—unknown—military commands, Eustathios had reached, according to ''[[Theophanes Continuatus]]'', the rank of ''[[patrikios]]'' and ''[[hypostrategos]]'' of the [[Anatolic Theme]]. The significance of the term "''hypostrategos''" has been debated; normally it would designate the second-in-command to the ''[[strategos]]'' or military governor of a [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]], but Vannier suggested that on account of his high title of ''patrikios'', Argyros was actually the ''strategos''.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=210}} ''Theophanes Continuatus'' further extols Argyros and mentions that he scored several successes against the [[Arabs]] in the east, most likely a reference to the great Byzantine victory over the Arabs of [[Tarsus (city)|Tarsus]] and [[Mopsuestia]] at [[Germanikeia]] in December 904, under the overall command of Andronikos Doukas.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}} He then fell into disgrace and was exiled. Although no details or reasons are offered for his exile, this has been interpreted by modern scholars as being connected to the failed rebellion and flight of Andronikos Doukas to the Arabs in 906–907. Eustathios was rehabilitated soon after; if indeed his disgrace was related to the flight of Andronikos Doukas, this happened likely in 907/8, when Andronikos Doukas' son [[Constantine Doukas (usurper)|Constantine]] escaped from his Arab exile and returned to Constantinople, where he was pardoned by Emperor Leo.{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}{{sfn|Guilland|1967|pp=570–571}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|pp=209–210, 211}} 

Eustathios was then appointed as ''strategos'' of the border theme of [[Charsianon]], a position notably inferior in rank to that of the Anatolics that he had held previously.{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}} The Argyros family, however, had strong connections with Charsianon, from which it hailed.{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=58}} There he received the return to imperial service of a number of [[Medieval Armenia|Armenian]] lords, [[Melias]], the three brothers Baasakios, Krigorikios and Pazounes, and Ismael, who were established as march-wardens along the Empire's eastern border.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=59}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=211}} Of them, Melias in particular would go on to become the founder of the theme of [[Lykandos]] and one of the main Byzantine leaders in the wars against the Arabs over the next 30 years.{{sfn|Guilland|1957|pp=206–207}}

In late 908 Eustathios Argyros was promoted to the rank of ''[[magistros]]''—the highest court dignity open to someone not a member of the imperial family—and the post of [[Drungary of the Watch]], i.e. commander of the [[Vigla (tagma)|imperial bodyguard]], and replaced as ''strategos'' of Charsianon by Constantine Doukas.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|pp=59–60}} About a year later, he fell again under Leo's suspicion, and was ordered to return to his family's estates at Charsianon. Again the reason is unknown; perhaps, according to Cheynet and Vannier, it was a result of the unreliability of the Armenian lords he had welcomed into the Empire, who frequently went over to the Arabs.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=60}} On the way, he died after taking poison by one of his servants, and was buried on Spynin, the summit of Mount Aran.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=211}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=60}} While historian [[Romilly James Heald Jenkins]] has suggested that Argyros' poisoning was done through an agent of the powerful and scheming court eunuch [[Samonas]], it more likely was suicide.{{sfn|Tougher|1997|pp=213, 218}} His two sons, [[Pothos Argyros (Domestic of the Schools)|Pothos]] and [[Leo Argyros (10th century)|Leo]], who served in the palace as [[manglabites]] (personal bodyguards of the emperor), arranged to have their father's body transferred for burial to the monastery of Saint Elizabeth in the Charsianon district, founded by Eustathios' father.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=211}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=60}}

== Family ==
Eustathios' sons Pothos and Leo would go on to hold senior military commands, including the post of [[Domestic of the Schools]] (commander-in-chief).{{sfn|Tougher|1997|p=211}}{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|pp=60–62}} Another son, Romanos, is known only from his participation in the [[Battle of Achelous (917)|Battle of Achelous]] in 917.{{sfn|Cheynet|Vannier|2003|p=62}} Leo Argyros married a daughter of Emperor [[Romanos I Lekapenos]] (r. 920–944), and was probably the grandfather or great-grandfather of Emperor [[Romanos III Argyros]] (r. 1028–1034).{{sfn|Guilland|1957|p=189}}

== Identity ==
Some modern scholars like R. J. H. Jenkins (''The 'Flight' of Samonas''), [[R. H. Dolley]] (''The Lord High Admiral Eustathios Argyros and the betrayal of Taormina to the African Arabs in 902'') and [[Ekkehard Eickhoff]] (''Seekrieg und Seepolitik zwischen Islam und Abendland'') consider Eustathios Argyros to have been identical with the contemporary admiral [[Eustathios Argyros (admiral under Leo VI)|Eustathios]], active in the years before 904, mainly due to the reference by the 11th-century historian [[John Skylitzes]] that Argyros pursued a career in the army as well as in the fleet. This identification is rejected by other scholars like [[J.-F. Vannier]] (''Familles byzantines: les Argyroi (IXe–XIIe siècles)'') and [[Rodolphe Guilland|R. Guilland]] (''Recherches sur les institutions byzantines''). Furthermore, the admiral is given the surname "Argyros" in some modern works that distinguish him from the general, while others reject the surname entirely. According to the ''[[Prosopographie der mittelbyzantinischen Zeit]]'', "a definitive decision can no longer be made", and the main argument for the two being different persons is the incompatibility of their careers: the admiral Eustathios likewise experienced a tumultuous career with accusations of treason, rehabilitation, and renewed disgrace, and it is unlikely that such a man would again be entrusted with senior posts.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Eustathios (#21836); Eustathios Argyros (#21828)}}

