{{short description|sign of death}} {{Signs of death}} '''Livor mortis''' ([[Latin]]: ''livor'' – "bluish color", ''mortis'' – "of death"), '''postmortem lividity''' (Latin: ''postmortem'' – "after death", ''lividity'' – "black and blue"), '''hypostasis''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: ''hypo'', meaning "under, beneath"; ''stasis'', meaning "a standing"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hypostasis|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/hypostasis|work=The Free Dictionary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hypo-|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/hypo-|work=The Free Dictionary}}</ref>) or '''suggillation''', is the fourth [[Stages of death|stage]] and one of the [[signs of death]]. It is a settling of the [[blood]] in the lower (dependent) portion of the body post mortem, causing a purplish red discoloration of the skin. When the heart stops functioning and is no longer agitating the blood, heavy red blood cells sink through the [[blood plasma|serum]] by action of gravity. The blood travels faster in hotter conditions (eg. a beach) and blood travels slower in colder conditions (eg. a mountain).
Livor mortis starts in 20–30 minutes, but is usually not observable by the [[human eye]] until two hours after death. The size of the patches increases in the next three to six hours, with maximum lividity occurring between eight and twelve hours after [[death]]. The blood pools into the [[interstitial fluid|interstitial tissues]] of the body. The intensity of the color depends upon the amount of reduced haemoglobin in the blood. The discoloration does not occur in the areas of the body that are in contact with the ground or another object, in which [[capillary|capillaries]] are compressed.<ref name=ManualOfFO>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=WQVCCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=pallor+mortis+dark+skin&source=bl&ots=Oco_ZDStoB&sig=7e7PGN0thLFUxQFiXz1DJtzMXH0&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=pallor%2520mortis%2520dark%2520skin&f=false|title=Manual of Forensic Odontology, Fifth Edition|last=Senn|first=David R.|last2=Weems|first2=Richard A.|date=2013-01-22|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1439851340|language=en}}</ref>
==Applicability== [[Coroner]]s can use the presence or absence of livor mortis as a means of determining an approximate time of death. It can also be used by [[forensic science|forensic]] investigators to determine whether or not a body has been moved. For instance, if the body is found lying [[prone position|prone]], but the pooling is present on the deceased's back, investigators can conclude that the body was originally positioned [[supine position|supine]].<ref name=ManualOfFO/>
Among coroners and other investigators, such as [[Detective|homicide and forensic detectives]], livor mortis is not considered an exact way to measure time of death, but instead is a way to [[Approximation|approximate]] it. Livor mortis, along with [[algor mortis]], [[rigor mortis]], and practices such as [[forensic entomology]] are frequently combined by investigators to more accurately pinpoint the estimated time of death.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books/about/Forensic_Pathology_Second_Edition.html?id=XyG3802xSdwC&redir_esc=y|title=Forensic Pathology, Second Edition|last=DiMaio|first=Dominick|last2=DiMaio|first2=Vincent J. M.|date=2001-06-28|publisher=CRC Press|year=|isbn=9781420042412|location=|pages=|language=en|via=}}</ref>
